  "text": "To overcome the problem of comparing predation rates on artificial and natural nests that had been monitored for different periods, we ensured that the maximum exposure periods of each of the four artificial nests equalled that of the corresponding natural nest. The maximum exposure period of an artificial nest equalled the number of days that elapsed between finding the corresponding natural nest and either the end of its associated breeding attempt (nests that were not depredated) or the estimated day of fledging had it been successful (depredated nests). If an artificial nest remained untouched by predators for this period, it was deemed successful; if the eggs were damaged or removed during this exposure period, it was classed as depredated. This meant that the overall predation rates on artificial and natural nests could be compared directly without using [CITATION_1] method of calculating daily predation rates.",
